But the move away from the "neoliberal professors' party" to the "party of the little man", announced by honorary chairman Alexander Gauland in 2016, is still a misnomer in 2023. The AfD relies on social envy, playing the various groups of "little people" off against each other. It combines this with strategic agitation, especially against the unemployed and immigrants. The AfD's programmatic demands primarily mean economic, ultimately only redistribution, from the bottom up.

In terms of content, the course combines right-wing culture war with unredeemable demands for peace and superficial social rhetoric. The AfD presents itself as the party of the "little people", especially in the energy crisis, stirs up fears of loss and gives racist answers to questions of distribution. The AfD is not only calling for withdrawal from the EU (program: AfD main motion: demand for EU dissolution) and NATO. The AfD is calling for the deregulation of the labor market, a reduction in corporate taxes, the abolition of the solidarity surcharge and a reduction in overall social spending. Deregulation of the labor market will loosen dismissal protection provisions. This will make workers more vulnerable and weaken social cohesion by increasing insecurity and fear of job loss. The dismantling of social safety nets will restrict access to state support, which will plunge people into financial hardship and increase social inequality even more. The expansion of wind power is to be stopped. 

Renewables in general are to be severely curbed. 

The Alternative for Germany is also strongly in favor of private sector solutions instead of state intervention. This is likely to lead to the privatization of state-owned companies and institutions, for example in the area of â€‹â€‹infrastructure or education. The privatizations demanded by the AfD will make access to basic services more difficult and increase social inequality even further, since not everyone is able to afford the private alternatives.
The conclusion of Professor Andreas Haufler, economist and professor at the Seminar for Economic Policy at the Ludwig Maximilian University in Munich: "I could not find anything in the AfD's program that would be good for the German economy. On the contrary: What the AfD is planning would make many things even worse."
The AfD rejects children's rights in the Basic Law as an infringement on parents' rights to raise their children.

The AfD is against basic child benefits, against inheritance tax, against wealth tax, against raising the top tax rate, against a retirement age. The AfD is a party for the elite and the rich. It's a shame that people choose the AfD, considering that there are over 50 parties in Germany that you can vote for.

2022 erschÃ¼ttert ein Korruptionsskandal BrÃ¼ssel und das EuropÃ¤ische Parlament. Im Zentrum: Eva Kaili, VizeprÃ¤sidentin des EuropÃ¤ischen Parlaments. Es geht um Korruption, um mutmaÃŸlich erkaufte politische Einflussnahme von Drittstaaten und Koffer voller Bargeld.

Es ist ein politisches Beben: Im Dezember 2022 erschÃ¼ttert ein Korruptionsskandal rund um die ehemalige ParlamentsvizeprÃ¤sidentin Eva Kaili â€“ auch â€Katargateâ€œ genannt - BrÃ¼ssel und die EU. Es geht um mutmaÃŸlich erkaufte Einflussnahme von Drittstaaten. Aktive und ehemalige EU-Abgeordnete wurden verhaftet, Ermittler beschlagnahmten Koffer voller Bargeld in den Wohnungen der Politiker, mutmaÃŸlich bezahlt von Marokko und Katar, die sich so Einfluss auf die Gesetzgebung in der EU erkaufen wollten.

â€Katargate bedroht die ganze Institutionâ€œ, sagt Nick Aiossa von â€Transparency Internationalâ€œ. Die ohnehin schwachen Ethikregeln des Parlaments wÃ¼rden kaum befolgt, VerstÃ¶ÃŸe seit Jahrzehnten so gut wie nie geahndet. Aiossa: â€Eine fatale Kultur der Straflosigkeit!â€œ. Steckt der Fehler im System?

Der Dokumentarfilm rekonstruiert â€Katargateâ€œ, den bislang grÃ¶ÃŸten Korruptionsskandal in der EU. Im Interview bezieht Eva Kaili als eine der Hauptbeschuldigten Stellung. Sie sieht sich als Opfer eines Justizskandals. Auch andere Beschuldigte, wie NiccolÃ² FigÃ -Talamanca und die unter Verdacht geratene EU-Abgeordnete Marie Arena geben Auskunft.

Der Dokumentarfilm nutzt Unterlagen und Protokolle der ErmittlungsbehÃ¶rden und der Bundesanwaltschaft in BrÃ¼ssel und verfolgt die Frage, was die EU-Institutionen der Einflussnahme entgegensetzen kÃ¶nnen und vor allem wollen. Ein System von mangelnder Transparenz und zu laschen Regeln wird erkennbar - der Wille nach AufklÃ¤rung und stÃ¤rkeren Anti-Korruptions-Gesetzen scheint kraftlos. Dabei steht angesichts von wachsendem Euroskeptizismus und den kommenden EU-Wahlen viel auf dem Spiel.  Zu sehen bei Arte. Anstatt auf andere rumzuhacken solltet ihr lieber LÃ¶sungen finden.
KommentarENG:
In 2022, a corruption scandal rocked Brussels and the European Parliament. At the center: Eva Kaili, Vice President of the European Parliament. It's about corruption, allegedly bought political influence from third countries and suitcases full of cash.

It's a political earthquake: In December 2022, a corruption scandal surrounding former Parliament Vice President Eva Kaili - also known as "Qatargate" - rocked Brussels and the EU. It's about allegedly bought influence from third countries. Current and former MEPs were arrested, investigators seized suitcases full of cash from politicians' homes, allegedly paid for by Morocco and Qatar, who wanted to buy influence over legislation in the EU.

"Qatargate threatens the entire institution," says Nick Aiossa of "Transparency International". The parliament's already weak ethics rules are hardly followed, and violations have hardly ever been punished for decades. Aiossa: "A fatal culture of impunity!" Is the fault in the system?

The documentary reconstructs "Qatargate", the biggest corruption scandal in the EU to date. In the interview, Eva Kaili takes a stand as one of the main accused. She sees herself as the victim of a judicial scandal. Other accused, such as NiccolÃ² FigÃ -Talamanca and the suspected MEP Marie Arena, also provide information.

The documentary uses documents and protocols from the investigative authorities and the Federal Prosecutor's Office in Brussels and pursues the question of what the EU institutions can and, above all, want to do to counteract the influence. A system of lacking transparency and too lax rules becomes apparent - the will for clarification and stronger anti-corruption laws seems powerless. In view of growing Euroscepticism and the upcoming EU elections, a lot is at stake. To be seen on Arte. Instead of picking on others, you should find solutions.

KommentarENG:
In 2022, a corruption scandal rocked Brussels and the European Parliament. At the center: Eva Kaili, Vice President of the European Parliament. It's about corruption, allegedly bought political influence from third countries and suitcases full of cash.

It's a political earthquake: In December 2022, a corruption scandal surrounding former Parliament Vice President Eva Kaili - also known as "Qatargate" - rocked Brussels and the EU. It's about allegedly bought influence from third countries. Current and former MEPs were arrested, investigators seized suitcases full of cash from politicians' homes, allegedly paid for by Morocco and Qatar, who wanted to buy influence over legislation in the EU.

"Qatargate threatens the entire institution," says Nick Aiossa of "Transparency International". The parliament's already weak ethics rules are hardly followed, and violations have hardly ever been punished for decades. Aiossa: "A fatal culture of impunity!" Is the fault in the system?

The documentary reconstructs "Qatargate", the biggest corruption scandal in the EU to date. In the interview, Eva Kaili takes a stand as one of the main accused. She sees herself as the victim of a judicial scandal. Other accused, such as NiccolÃ² FigÃ -Talamanca and the suspected MEP Marie Arena, also provide information.

The documentary uses documents and protocols from the investigative authorities and the Federal Prosecutor's Office in Brussels and pursues the question of what the EU institutions can and, above all, want to do to counteract the influence. A system of lacking transparency and too lax rules becomes apparent - the will for clarification and stronger anti-corruption laws seems powerless. In view of growing Euroscepticism and the upcoming EU elections, a lot is at stake. To be seen at PhÃ¶nix. Instead of rushing, it would be good to just tackle things. You have a responsibility to us. You talk a lot and say nothing. Actions count more than words

The Excessive: Baerbock squandered 11,000 euros on styling and hairstyles in November alone

Federal Foreign Minister Annalena Baerbock (Greens) is not only a real risk for Germany with her foreign policy. Her penchant for self-promotion is also a threat - to German taxpayers' money. Her consistently high hair and styling costs have already angered the Federal Audit Office - and the Taxpayers' Association as well.

She spent a whopping 11,900 euros on styling measures in November 2023. This once again puts Burbock well above the costs incurred by other politicians in the same month.The Union is not happy about Burbock's exorbitant new spending.

This may seem like some kind of joke or satire, but it is the reality. It is not entirely clear how one can spend so much money on hair styling and the like, but she manages it perfectly. It is obvious to everyone that this is a colossal expenditure, probably not their money but ours, for whatever, when our country is going through an economic and migration crisis. When hard-working taxpayers spend five-figure sums every month on Annalena Burbock's hair, the fun stops. We need a cap on federal spending on hairdressing and cosmetic services. Because Bairbock's 11,000 euros is an abuse and clearly too much.

FÃ¼r die kommende Sitzungswoche habe ich ein sehr wichtiges Anliegen:
Ich mach mir sehr groÃŸe Sorgen um den Hungerstreikenden Michael Winter. Er und andere sind seit Wochen in Berlin im Hungerstreik fÃ¼r Klimaehrlichkeit. DafÃ¼r, dass Olaf Scholz einfach nur ehrlich ausspricht, dass wir zuviel CO2 in der AtmosphÃ¤re haben. Mehr nicht. Keine groÃŸe Forderung. Ihm geht es zunehmend schlechter und er riskiert dafÃ¼r im Moment sein Leben. Ich habe ihn auf verschiedenen Klimaprotesten kennengelernt. Er hat mich inspiriert und ich habe ihn tief in mein Herz geschlossen. Ich war nie dafÃ¼r, dass er in den Hungerstreik geht, da ich nicht die Hoffnung hatte das Olaf Scholz etwas dazu sagt und Michael ohnehin davor schon sehr wenig gewogen hat. Der Kanzler hat leider zu oft bewiesen, dass er ziemlich gut schweigen kann. Um trotzdem das unmÃ¶gliche mÃ¶glich zu machen bitte ich sie dringlichst kommende Woche an der Sitzungswoche auf Ihren Kollegen Olaf Scholz einzuwirken und zu versuchen, dass Ã¼ber das Thema zumindest geredet wird. Er muss nichtmal KlimaschutzmaÃŸnahmen ankÃ¼ndigen, sondern einfach nur ehrlich Ã¼ber den aktuellen Zustand berichten. Wenn Sie den Kanzler nicht Ã¼berzeugen kÃ¶nnen/wollen, vielleicht kÃ¶nnen Sie zumindest Michael Winter Ã¼berzeugen seinen Hungerstreik trotzdem zu beenden und nehmen Sie Kontakt mit ihm auf. Danke!
KommentarENG:
Dear Katarina Barley, 
I have a very important concern for the coming week of meetings:
I am very worried about the hunger striker Michael Winter. He and others have been on hunger strike in Berlin for weeks for climate honesty. For Olaf Scholz to simply say honestly that we have too much CO2 in the atmosphere. Nothing more. Not a big demand. He is getting worse and worse and is currently risking his life for it. I met him at various climate protests. He inspired me and I took him deep into my heart. I was never in favor of him going on hunger strike because I had no hope that Olaf Scholz would say anything about it and Michael was already very unimportant beforehand. Unfortunately, the Chancellor has proven too often that he is pretty good at keeping quiet. In order to make the impossible possible, I urgently ask you to influence your colleague Olaf Scholz next week during the meeting week and try to at least get the issue discussed. He doesn't even have to announce climate protection measures, he just has to report honestly about the current situation. If you can't/don't want to convince the Chancellor, maybe you can at least convince Michael Winter to end his hunger strike anyway and get in touch with him. Thank you!

KommentarDEU: Bei den MilankoviÄ‡-Zyklen (nach dem serbischen Mathematiker[2] Milutin MilankoviÄ‡, 1879â€“1958) handelt es sich um langperiodische VerÃ¤nderungen der globalen Verteilung der auf der Erde eintreffenden Sonnenstrahlung Ã¼ber die jÃ¤hrliche Schwankungsbreite hinaus. Die Erdbahn um die Sonne, die PrÃ¤zession der Erdrotationsachse sowie die Neigung der Erdachse und damit die wechselnden Einfallswinkel der Sonneneinstrahlung auf der Nord- und SÃ¼dhemisphÃ¤re unterliegen verschiedenen Orbitalzeitskalen mit einer Dauer von 25.800 bis etwa 100.000 beziehungsweise 405.000 Jahren. Sie erklÃ¤ren teilweise die natÃ¼rlichen KlimaverÃ¤nderungen vor allem wÃ¤hrend des QuartÃ¤rs und sind daher fÃ¼r die Klimatologie und PalÃ¤oklimatologie von groÃŸer Bedeutung.
KommentarENG: The MilankoviÄ‡ cycles (named after the Serbian mathematician[2] Milutin MilankoviÄ‡, 1879â€“1958) are long-period changes in the global distribution of solar radiation reaching the Earth beyond the annual fluctuation range. The Earth's orbit around the sun, the precession of the Earth's rotation axis and the inclination of the Earth's axis and thus the changing angles of incidence of solar radiation in the northern and southern hemispheres are subject to different orbital time scales with a duration of 25,800 to about 100,000 and 405,000 years respectively. I would really like to vote for you, but with a chancellor who doesn't want to risk a bit more European sovereignty, who simply can't control his business and who makes fun of citizens in such an aloof way, that's impossible for me. If the SPD prevents Ursula von der Leyen from becoming Commission President, gives the FDP a clear dressing down and, in the time remaining until the federal election, takes a clear position on how it would finally redistribute in a red-green federal government and wants to advance climate protection with social responsibility; if it finally strengthens the Bundeswehr and doesn't just slow down its defense minister - then I'll vote for the SPD in 2025 despite Scholz. Instead of pitting citizens' income recipients and refugees against each other, defending the "pension at 63" but completely abandoning young people and, last but not least, considering a stock pension, the SPD should make fair citizens' insurance at all levels its main issue, make civil servants pay into the insurance systems and finally tax capital more heavily in order to relieve the burden on employees at the same time.

The almost three percent party will never leave the coalition despite all of the Greens' legitimate demands.
